# OtoDock Configuration
# Copy to config.env and edit. Secrets auto-generate on first run if omitted.
# This file is the single source of truth for all services (proxy, phone, Docker MCPs).

# ── Auto-generated secrets (leave blank for auto-generation on first run) ──
PROXY_API_KEY=
JWT_SECRET=
VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=

# ── Database ──
# `proxy/setup.sh` auto-generates a strong POSTGRES_PASSWORD + matching
# DATABASE_URL into config.env on a FRESH install, and the bundled `postgres`
# service reads POSTGRES_PASSWORD via `docker compose --env-file config.env`
# (it refuses to start with a default password). Leave both blank to let
# setup.sh handle it; set them explicitly for a managed/remote database. A
# fully-dockerized proxy points the host at `otodock-postgres:5432` (compose
# network) instead of localhost.
# POSTGRES_PASSWORD=
# DATABASE_URL=postgresql://otodock:CHANGE_ME@localhost:5432/otodock

# ── Server ──
# Bare-metal: the port the proxy binds. Docker (T2): the published HOST port —
# the container side stays 8400 (pinned in docker-compose.yml), so e.g.
# PROXY_PORT=8410 serves the same stack on :8410 without touching the image.
PROXY_PORT=8400
# Server timezone (IANA, e.g. Europe/Athens). On the FIRST install the platform
# timezone defaults to this server's local time (task scheduling / cron / agent
# datetime), instead of UTC — set once, never overwritten by updates or an
# admin's later change. Bare-metal reads /etc/localtime automatically; a Docker
# proxy is UTC unless you set TZ here (the compose passes it into the container).
# TZ=Europe/Athens
# Public URL of the dashboard. Also decides the session-cookie `Secure` flag:
# an https:// URL → Secure cookies (correct, incl. behind a TLS-terminating
# reverse proxy); an http:// URL (localhost/LAN, pre-TLS) → NON-Secure so the
# browser actually keeps the login cookie (a Secure cookie is dropped over http,
# which makes login appear to work then 401 everywhere). Override with
# COOKIE_SECURE=true/false if your edge differs from this URL's scheme.
# The proxy serves the dashboard itself — same host/port as the API (keep the
# port in sync with PROXY_PORT above); set your real public URL when fronted
# by a reverse proxy / tunnel (e.g. https://otodock.example.com).
DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL=http://localhost:8400
# COOKIE_SECURE=
VAPID_EMAIL=admin@localhost

# ── OtoDock relay (hosted native push, hosted OAuth, license activation) ──
# A connected install reaches the live OtoDock relay by DEFAULT (no config) —
# that's how native mobile push works with ZERO Firebase server credentials on
# your side: the relay holds OtoDock's FCM service account. Two opt-outs:
#   OTODOCK_AIR_GAPPED=true     # make this install reach OtoDock NOT AT ALL
#   OTODOCK_RELAY_BASE=...      # override endpoint (staging / private relay)
# BYO-Firebase escape hatch (advanced) — send native push from your OWN Firebase
# project instead of the relay (rebuild the app w/ your own google-services.json):
#   FCM_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_PATH=/path/to/your-fcm-service-account.json

# ── Managed / OtoDock-cloud installs (operator-only — leave unset to self-host) ──
# OTODOCK_CLOUD=true marks an OtoDock-operated install (the control plane manages
# connectivity + licensing). Self-hosters leave it unset.
#   OTODOCK_CLOUD=true
# OTODOCK_FORCED_SETTINGS pins platform_settings the customer-admin must NOT change:
# a JSON object {key: value}. The forced value wins on every read, writes to it are
# ignored, and the admin UI hides/locks it. Bools may be JSON true/false (stored as
# "1"/""). Fail-safe: blank / invalid JSON / non-object → ignored. Do NOT include
# license_key here (use OTODOCK_LICENSE_KEY — forcing it would freeze relay re-issue).
#   OTODOCK_FORCED_SETTINGS={"session_retention_enabled":true,"session_retention_days":"180","smtp_host":"mail.otodock.io","smtp_port":"587","password_min_score":"3"}
# OTODOCK_LICENSE_KEY seeds platform_settings.license_key ONCE at startup when the DB
# has none (bootstrap on container rebuild). The license_check_worker then owns updates
# via the relay re-issue — this is a seed, never an override.
#   OTODOCK_LICENSE_KEY=otolic_...
# OTODOCK_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY / OTODOCK_TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY — Cloudflare Turnstile login
# bot-protection. When BOTH are set they take precedence over the DB and the admin sees
# only a read-only "managed" badge (keys never exposed, admin writes ignored). Use these
# dedicated vars (NOT OTODOCK_FORCED_SETTINGS, which would show the value) to keep the
# secret hidden. Self-hosters leave these blank and set their own keys in Setup → Security.
#   OTODOCK_TURNSTILE_SITE_KEY=0x4AAAAAAA...
#   OTODOCK_TURNSTILE_SECRET_KEY=0x4AAAAAAA...

# ── Sandbox network isolation (ALWAYS ON — no toggle) ──
# Every LOCAL agent sandbox (CLI / Codex / Direct-LLM stdio MCPs) is wrapped in a
# pasta network namespace: NAT'd outbound internet only, with RFC1918 + the
# host's own subnet + cloud-metadata blackholed at the kernel level. Egress is
# carved ONLY to the proxy hook port + each session's configured MCP / docker-MCP
# / local-LLM targets (auto-derived). Requires `passt` (pasta) + `iproute2` +
# unprivileged user namespaces — the proxy HARD-FAILS startup if they're missing
# (the installer sets them up). There is NO un-isolated mode: for genuinely
# un-isolated execution, use a remote machine. Satellites are unaffected (no
# bwrap there).

# ── Phone Server (optional — only needed if phone features are used) ──
PHONE_SERVER_URL=http://127.0.0.1:9093
# The address your PBX dials to reach the phone daemon (AudioSocket :9092 +
# register API :9093) — baked into the generated dialplan snippet. Auto-detected
# from the default-route interface, which is correct on bare metal but WRONG
# inside Docker (it picks the unreachable container-internal IP): in the
# containerised deployment set this to the Docker HOST's LAN IP.
# OTO_AUDIOSOCKET_PUBLIC_HOST=192.168.1.10
# DEEPGRAM_API_KEY=
# CARTESIA_API_KEY=

# ── Audio/Video playback (optional) ──
# ffmpeg/ffprobe transcode non-web-native media (e.g. iPhone HEVC) so audio and
# video play inline in chat + workspace. PROXY-SIDE ONLY — never exposed to the
# agent sandbox or satellites. Leave blank to use the host PATH (dev). In
# production point these at a path OUTSIDE the sandbox-mounted system dirs
# (/usr,/bin,/lib,/sbin) so a sandboxed process can't even see the binary:
#   OTO_FFMPEG_PATH=/opt/otodock/bin/ffmpeg
#   OTO_FFPROBE_PATH=/opt/otodock/bin/ffprobe
# OTO_FFMPEG_PATH=
# OTO_FFPROBE_PATH=
# Transcode/remux cache (default: <PLATFORM_DATA_DIR>/media-cache).
# OTO_MEDIA_CACHE_DIR=

# ── SSO / OIDC (optional — enables single sign-on) ──
# Works with Authentik, Keycloak, Authelia, oauth2-proxy, Cloudflare Access, etc.
# Discovery URL is fetched at startup; the four endpoint URLs auto-derive.
# OIDC_REDIRECT_URI auto-derives to ${DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL}/auth/callback.
# OIDC_ENABLED=true
# OIDC_PROVIDER_NAME=SSO                                    # button label: "Sign in with <name>"
# OIDC_DISCOVERY_URL=https://auth.example.com/application/o/<app-slug>/.well-known/openid-configuration
# OIDC_CLIENT_ID=
# OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET=
# Role group mapping — name your provider's groups and reference them here.
# Missing env vars = that role isn't mapped (group membership is ignored).
# OIDC_ROLE_ADMIN_GROUP=OtoDock Admin
# OIDC_ROLE_CREATOR_GROUP=OtoDock Creator
# OIDC_ROLE_MEMBER_GROUP=OtoDock Member
# Advanced: override individual endpoints if your provider doesn't expose
# discovery, or to pin a specific URL:
# OIDC_AUTHORIZE_URL=    OIDC_TOKEN_URL=    OIDC_USERINFO_URL=    OIDC_LOGOUT_URL=
# OIDC_SCOPES=openid profile email groups
# OIDC_REDIRECT_URI=                                        # override auto-derive

# ── Collabora Online (document editing/preview) ──
#
# OSS DEFAULT — sub-path mode. Just set DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL above and
# everything else auto-derives:
#   COLLABORA_URL              = ${DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL}/collabora
#   COLLABORA_FRAME_ANCESTORS  = host of DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL
#   COLLABORA_SERVICE_ROOT     = /collabora
#   COLLABORA_BACKEND_URL      = http://localhost:9981  (compose: http://collabora:9980)
# The platform proxy reverse-proxies /collabora/* to the Collabora container
# internally — your reverse proxy / Cloudflare Tunnel only needs the dashboard
# upstream, no per-route blocks. Document preview works out of the box.
#
# To override (only if you need a non-default deployment shape):
#
#   Subdomain mode (Collabora on a separate FQDN, e.g. behind a different auth):
#     COLLABORA_URL=https://collabora.example.com
#     # COLLABORA_FRAME_ANCESTORS auto-derived from DASHBOARD_PUBLIC_URL host
#
#   Cloud / OtoDock-hosted central Collabora:
#     COLLABORA_URL=https://collabora.otodock.io
#     # WOPI_BASE_URL must be publicly reachable from central Collabora
#
# COLLABORA_URL=
# COLLABORA_FRAME_ANCESTORS=

# WOPI_BASE_URL = the URL Collabora uses to call back into the proxy to fetch
# and save files. Must be reachable from the Collabora container (often the
# proxy's LAN IP + port, not the public hostname). Defaults to http://127.0.0.1:{PROXY_PORT}.
# WOPI_BASE_URL=http://192.168.1.10:8400

# COLLABORA_BACKEND_URL = where the platform proxy reaches Collabora internally.
# Default: http://localhost:9981 (native install / dev). Compose deployments
# should set http://collabora:9980 (service DNS).
# COLLABORA_BACKEND_URL=http://localhost:9981

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Session concurrency / memory admission (small-host tuning)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Full design: proxy/docs/architecture/CONCURRENCY.md. New local sessions pass
# two gates: a reservation budget (Gate 1) and a live free-RAM veto (Gate 2,
# reclaimable-aware, sidecar-aware). Denials name their real cause ("busy" =
# sessions hold the box; "host memory" = something else eats the RAM), idle
# sessions are auto-evicted to make room when session pressure is the cause,
# and an EMPTY platform always admits its first session (swap-backed) rather
# than hard-locking. Defaults suit 8GB+; on a 4-8GB VM you mostly leave these
# alone and let eviction/veto do their job — sizing intuition: a CLI session
# reserves 850MB, a Direct-LLM session 250MB, so 4GB fits about 1-2 heavy or
# 3-4 light sessions alongside postgres/collabora/MCP sidecars.
#
# Per-session memory reserve estimates (MB). Lower HEAVY below measured RSS
# only if you accept packing tighter than the real footprint.
# SESSION_EST_HEAVY_MB=850
# SESSION_EST_LIGHT_MB=250
#
# Gate-2 swap credit (MB): live free-RAM gains min(SwapFree/2, this) so a
# small box WITH swap packs one more session by paging cold heap. 0 disables.
# SESSION_SWAP_CREDIT_MB=512
#
# Gate-1 budget fraction of the proxy's memory total (generous by design --
# Gate 2 is the real safety).
# BUDGET_FRACTION=0.90
#
# Gate-2 floor: live free RAM (MB) that must REMAIN after admitting. Effective
# floor = max(this, 3% of total).
# SESSION_RESERVE_FLOOR_MB=256
#
# Minimum idle age (seconds) before a session may be evicted to admit another.
# SESSION_EVICT_FLOOR_S=300
#
# Optional hard cap on concurrent local sessions (0 = off). An operator escape
# hatch -- the memory gates are the intended control.
# OTODOCK_MAX_LOCAL_SESSIONS=0
#
# T2 (docker-compose) only: proxy container memory cap. Default 0 = uncapped
# (deliberate -- Gate 2 reads host MemAvailable and sessions may lean on swap).
# Set e.g. 12g for hard OOM containment of the proxy tree; the sidecar-leak
# veto stays active either way (capped Gate 2 = min(cgroup, host)).
# OTODOCK_PROXY_MEM_LIMIT=0
#
# Default memory cap injected into docker-MCP sidecar containers whose compose
# declares no limit of its own (an MCP's explicit mem_limit always wins; a
# json-file log-rotation default rides along the same way). Applied on T1 via
# the generated compose override and on T2 via the pull rewrite, with
# memswap_limit = mem_limit. Set 0/none to disable injection.
# OTODOCK_MCP_DEFAULT_MEM_LIMIT=2g
